To show that a decreasing sequence \emph{b}\textsubscript{\emph{n}}
converges, you have to show that it is bounded.

Let's consider a few simpler examples to understand the relation between
\emph{a}\textsubscript{\emph{n}} and \emph{b}\textsubscript{\emph{n}}
better.

E.g. consider the sequence

\begin{align*}
a_n = (-1)^n \quad \text{for all } n \geq 1
\end{align*}

or the other sequence

\begin{align*}
a_n = \sin\left(\frac{n}{10}\right) \quad \text{for all } n \geq 1
\end{align*}

Both sequences are bounded and satisfy

\begin{align*}
-1 \leq a_n \leq 1 \quad\text{for all } n \geq 1
\end{align*}

Now in each case, consider the corresponding sequence
\emph{b}\textsubscript{\emph{n}} as describe in the question and
observe. Note that those two cases are fairly easy as what will happen
to that sequence (which you should be able to show converges).

A more subtle case to consider after these two is the case of the
sequence

\begin{align*}
a_n = \frac{n+10}{n}\sin\left(\frac{n}{10}\right) \quad \text{for all } n \geq 1
\end{align*}
Notice that the first rational term converges to 1, but because of the
sine term, that sequence will never converge. What will happen to the
corresponding sequence \emph{b}\textsubscript{\emph{n}} in this case?
Why does \emph{b}\textsubscript{\emph{n}} converge?
